<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1941-12-29T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1941-12-29T00:00:00-05:00" n="81" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d81">
                                <note rend="inline" type="source">Hopkins Papers</note>
                                <head>
                                    <hi rend="italic">The President’s Special Assistant</hi>
                                        (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Hopkins</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">President</gloss>
                                    </hi>
                                </head>
                                <opener>
                                    <seg rendition="#center">[Extract]<note n="1" xml:id="d81fn1">The omitted paragraphs of this memorandum refer to the
                                            Joint Declaration of Allied unity; see <hi rend="italic">post</hi>, <ref target="#pg_373">p.
                                            373</ref>.</note></seg>
                                </opener>
                                <opener>
                                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                                        <placeName>
                                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1941-12-29">December 29,
                                            1941</date>.</dateline>
                                </opener>
                                <p rend="center">. . . . . . . . . . . . . .</p>
                                <pb facs="0215" n="141" xml:id="pg_141"/>
                                <p rend="center"><hi rend="smallcaps">St. Pierre &amp;
                                    Miquelon</hi></p>
                                <p>The Prime Minister just phoned me at 6:45,<note n="2" xml:id="d81fn2">Churchill was in Ottawa on December 29–30
                                        and the morning of December 31, returning to Washington late
                                        that evening.</note> reading me a cable from the Foreign
                                    Office to him, in which they indicate the most strenuous
                                    objection to the ousting of the Free French from Miquelon.<note n="3" xml:id="d81fn3">See the editorial note on the
                                        Churchill-Hull conversation on December 28, <hi rend="italic">ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_131">p.
                                            131</ref>.</note></p>
                                <p>They claim de Gaulle will not issue the orders to throw his
                                    commander out.</p>
                                <p>The burden of the message was that the whole business would kick
                                    up an unbelievable row, for which we could give no good public
                                    explanation. In spite of the fact that de Gaulle acted in bad
                                    faith, the British don’t see how he can be forced out and think
                                    that the use of force would be very bad.</p>
                                <closer>
                                    <signed>H. L. H.</signed>
                                </closer>
                            </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>